Compared to other common metal ions, only Hg2+ can significantly quench the fluorescence intensity of the CDs (Fig. 5
                           a). This specific fluorescence quenching may be due to the strong interactions between Hg2+ and the surface functional groups on the CDs, which cause photoelectrons to migrate from the surface of the CDs to Hg2+ [27]. In addition, the presence of potential interference metal ions does not affect Hg2+ detection (Fig. 5b). Fig. 5c shows the fluorescence spectra for different concentrations of Hg2+ added to the CDs. It can be seen from Fig. 5d that the fluorescence quenching efficiency I0/I has a good linear relationship with the concentration of Hg2+ and conforms to the Stern-Volmer equation: I0/I = 1 + KSV[Q], in which I0 and I are the fluorescence intensities of the CDs before and after Hg2+ addition, and the excitation wavelength is 360 nm. KSV and [Q] are the fluorescence quenching constant and the concentration of Hg2+, respectively. A linear equation is obtained for the range of 0–45 μM Hg2+: I0/I - 1 = 0.00279 [Hg2+] - 0.0175 (μM) (R2 = 0.99724, n = 10). The minimum detection limit of the final CD sensor towards Hg2+ is 0.09 μM, which is lower than that of most previously reported Hg2+ detection assays (see Table 1
                           ). The results show that the nitrogen-doped CDs can detect Hg2+ with high sensitivity and thus have certain practical significance.
